York Peninsula where collecting recommenced, there having been a break from the time at the Cumberland Islands. In the Gulf of Car- pentaria [27—31] more than four months (early November, 1802, to early March, 1803) were spent surveying the coasts around to Arnhem Bay [32]. While in the Gulf it was found that the timbers of the ship were in a dangerous state of disrepair, and from Arnhem Bay, partly owing to this and partly to the advancing season of the year, F LINDERs sailed for Timor. They returned to Port Jackson by circumnavigating the continent, the only stop being for a brief call at Goose Island Bay [3] on the south coast of Western Australia. This is recorded by BROWN'S notes on a few specimenS.
